THE PALE QUEEN'S COMPACT
A 5-Adventure Mini-Campaign for the Parks Group

THE GRAND MYSTERY COMPONENTS
The True Crime Ismara is conducting a territorial claim ritual across Skyrim - marking living people with Atmoran sigil components, who then freeze in place at specific geographic coordinates, forming nodes in a massive magical network. The completed ritual will anchor her cognitive dominion over Skyrim's landscape. She also intends to seize the Eye of Magnus as the power source to make this permanent and to erect a barrier that prevents Alduin's resurrection. She needs the party to make all of this happen because she cannot move through the modern world alone.
The Perpetrators
Ismara, who the party freed and is now traveling with
The party themselves, who are either wittingly or unwittingly enabling her
The Deception The party told Winterhold she was dead. Winterhold is now nearly dead because the cold never stopped. No one is looking for the real cause.
The Incompetent Officials
Jarl Korir: Trusts the party completely. Doesn't know he's been lied to. Currently focused on keeping his last few survivors alive.
Arch-Mage Savos Aren: Knows something is wrong with the cold. Doesn't know what. His experiments are well-intentioned and making things measurably worse.
Jarl Ulfric Stormcloak (Windhelm): Politically preoccupied. Sees the spreading cold as a natural Skyrim winter. Wrong.

THE PLAYER THREADS TO WEAVE IN
The Khajiit - Has rotjoint from sleeping with Ismara. This is the party member with the most intimate, complicated relationship with her. They are her closest point of contact. Their arc is about what that relationship actually means and what they're willing to do or sacrifice.
The Orc - Cannibalized their dead character. Namira is watching. This doesn't need to be a main plot thread but it should breathe in the background - small moments, strange dreams, an unusual comfort with darkness and rot. Namira and Ismara are not allies but they occupy adjacent philosophical space. This creates interesting texture.

THE 5 ADVENTURES

ADVENTURE 1: THE GRAY QUARTER
Location: Windhelm
What's Actually Happening Ismara has already begun her ritual. In the weeks since Frostmere, several people in the region have developed unexplained Atmoran rune markings on their skin - not wounds, not tattoos, something that appeared from within. They behave normally for a while, then one day they walk somewhere specific and freeze solid in place. Standing upright. Eyes open. Perfectly preserved. The city guard thinks it's a disease. The Hall of the Dead priests think it's a curse. Nobody connects it to the Pale Lady because the Pale Lady is dead.
The party arrives seeking a cure for rotjoint. This gets them into the Hall of the Dead, which sits above ancient Nordic catacombs beneath the city - catacombs that predate Windhelm itself.
The Incompetent Official The Hall of the Dead's priest has quarantined three people with the markings and is calling it the Pale Fever. He wants it gone. He will hire the party to investigate because the city guard won't touch it.
What the Party Can Discover
The markings are Atmoran runes. Old enough that almost nobody can read them. A scholar at the Palace of the Kings has a partial translation - they're geometric notation, like coordinates or structural anchors. Not a message. Not a warning. Scaffolding.
The frozen people are still alive inside. Their eyes track movement. One of them is weeping frozen tears.
The catacombs beneath the Hall of the Dead contain evidence of an earlier attempt at this same ritual - ancient, failed, abandoned. Whoever tried this before got as far as placing seven nodes before something stopped them. The geometry of the node placements, if mapped, points outward toward the horizon in every direction from a central point.
The central point, when calculated, is Frostmere.
The Namira Thread In the Gray Quarter, there's a beggar named Suvaris who has been eating the flesh of the frozen. She says it whispers to her. She isn't wrong. Namira's influence is subtle here - not a quest, just a presence. The Orc may feel a strange kinship with her they can't explain.
What Ismara Does She places her own node while they're in the city. Calmly. Efficiently. If the party watches, they see her choose a specific Nord laborer, touch him briefly, and walk away. Within an hour he has the markings. She writes nothing to explain this. She doesn't need to. They either understand she's working or they ask her. If they ask, she writes: This one is necessary.
End of Adventure The party now knows: this is a deliberate, massive ritual. They don't know what it does. They don't know how to stop it. They have a partial map of node placements and a central point at Frostmere. The rotjoint has a treatment in Windhelm (painful, expensive, not a cure - just management) from an alchemist who recognizes it as a contact curse from the undead.

ADVENTURE 2: THE PALE ROAD
Location: The road between Windhelm and Winterhold / the frozen wilderness
What's Actually Happening The party has to cross the region where the cold is worst. This adventure is about the journey itself - what it looks like to travel through a landscape Ismara is actively claiming. And it's about the party's relationship with her deepening or fracturing.
This is the most character-driven adventure. Low external plot pressure. High interpersonal pressure.
What They See The frozen people are everywhere out here. Dozens of them. Standing in fields, in forests, on hilltops. The geometry of their placement, if anyone is mapping it, is becoming clearer. It's a massive circle. Winterhold is at the center.
Bersi's farm is here. His family returned after the party came back with news. The ice covering it has not melted. Erik, the boy, is frozen in the yard. Still alive. Eyes tracking. He wandered out there two days ago and stopped.
What Ismara Does She places nodes. She also, for the first time, makes a demand of the party that has genuine moral weight. There is a village ahead, small, perhaps thirty people. She needs two of them. She writes: This will not kill them. Choose, or I will.
The Core Tension Do they choose? Do they refuse? Do they try to negotiate? Do they run ahead and warn the village? Whatever they do has consequences - either with Ismara or with the villagers. There is no clean answer.
What Can Be Discovered An Atmoran scholar's ruin near the road contains inscriptions that, with time and effort, allow fuller translation of the rune system. The sigil is a territorial ward - a massive magical claim. In the First Era it was used by Atmoran warlords to declare sovereignty over land. Completing it would tie the land itself to the caster's will. The cold is a byproduct of her ice matrix spreading outward as the ritual progresses.
End of Adventure The party arrives at the edge of Winterhold. It's nearly gone. A handful of survivors in the Frozen Hearth. Dagny is still there. She looks at the party with an expression that is not accusatory but is absolutely exhausted. She says: The College is still standing. They sent word they know what's causing this. They want to meet.

ADVENTURE 3: WHAT THE COLLEGE KNOWS
Location: College of Winterhold
What's Actually Happening Savos Aren has been studying the cold for weeks. He has pieced together that it's ritual in origin, Atmoran in structure, and that the geometry of the frozen people forms a containment ward on a massive scale. He does not know who is doing it. He does not know about Ismara.
He does know that at the center of the ward, there is a power source - something ancient and cold beneath Frostmere. And he knows that the Eye of Magnus, which the College has been studying for decades, resonates with it. The two artifacts are connected in ways he doesn't understand and that frankly terrify him.
The Incompetent Official Savos Aren is not incompetent - he's a brilliant mage. His flaw is that he's been studying the Eye of Magnus and has become subtly influenced by it. He genuinely wants to help. He also, without knowing it, wants the Eye more than he wants to admit. His advice will be slightly off in ways that only become clear in retrospect.
What the Party Can Discover
The Eye of Magnus predates the College. The College was built around it. They didn't find it - they found this spot because of it.
The Eye is not a weapon. It is a lens. It focuses and amplifies magical energy. If Ismara's ward were powered by the Eye, it would be permanent, unchallengeable, and continent-spanning.
There are notes in the restricted archive about Hjolmar Ice-Shaper. Not much. A name in a lineage of Nordic artificers. A reference to cognitive matrix theory. Nothing actionable yet - just a thread.
One of the College apprentices has the markings. He appeared two days ago. He doesn't know. He's acting normal.
What Ismara Does She doesn't enter the College. She waits. She writes to the party: The Arch-Mage has what I need. Learn where he keeps it.
This is the moment the party most clearly understands: she wants the Eye. They are being asked to be her scouts inside the one institution that might be able to stop her.
The Namira Thread There is a locked lower chamber in the College that Savos Aren will not discuss. The Orc feels drawn to it. Whatever is in there smells of very old death.
End of Adventure The party has a choice to make. They now know what Ismara's endgame is. They know where the Eye is. They know the College is the last institution capable of opposing her. They also know she is right there, outside, waiting.

ADVENTURE 4: THE WEIGHT OF IT
Location: Frostmere / the surrounding wilderness / back to Windhelm
What's Actually Happening This is the tipping point adventure. The sigil is nearly complete. The frozen people number in the hundreds across the region. Winterhold is essentially dead. The College is the last populated stronghold.
Ismara needs one more thing before she's ready to take the Eye: she needs to return to Frostmere and complete the central node of the ritual. The collapsed throne room needs to be cleared. She can do this herself, but she needs the party to hold the perimeter - the Dragon Cult has been watching, and they will try to stop her.
The Dragon Cult Connection This is the first time the Dragon Cult appears as an active threat. They don't want Ismara to succeed - a permanent anti-Alduin ward across Skyrim is a direct threat to their mission. They have been sending agents to destroy the frozen node-people before the ritual completes. Several of the "mysteriously unfrozen" corpses the party may have noticed along the road were Dragon Cult interference.
They are not the main antagonists of this campaign. They are an obstacle. But their presence confirms: Ismara's ritual genuinely threatens Alduin's return. She is not lying about that purpose.
The Central Question While the party holds the perimeter at Frostmere, they have time to think. Possibly to talk among themselves. The Khajiit has been closest to all of this. The Orc has been watching something change in themselves.
The ritual will make Ismara the sovereign of Skyrim. She will rule. Badly, by human standards. But Alduin will not return while she does.
Is that acceptable?
What Can Be Discovered In the collapsed Frostmere throne room while Ismara works, there are the remains of the original Dragon Cult sealing ritual. With the Hjolmar thread in mind and whatever research the party has done, it becomes possible to understand: the Ice Crown is her matrix, yes, but it is also incomplete. She was sealed before she could finish it. The cognitive matrix tech she and Hjolmar developed requires a final resonance anchor to be truly stable. The Eye of Magnus is that anchor. Without it, her matrix is brilliant but fragile. The crown could, theoretically, be disrupted.
They are not meant to find this. There's no sign pointing to it. It's there in the architecture of the sealing ritual if someone looks carefully and knows what they're looking for.
End of Adventure The central node is complete. The sigil is active but unpowered - a massive magical structure stretching across the entire region, waiting for the Eye to light it up. Ismara writes to the party:
It is time.

ADVENTURE 5: THE SIEGE OF THE COLLEGE
Location: College of Winterhold
What's Actually Happening Ismara moves on the College. This is not a battle in the traditional sense - she doesn't have an army. She has the party, her ice magic, and the weight of everything she's already built.
The College knows something is coming. Savos Aren has been preparing. But his preparations are based on incomplete information and his subtle Eye-influenced thinking has led him toward defending the Eye rather than destroying it.
The Structure This adventure is a gauntlet of decisions, not combat rooms.
The College has three layers of resistance:
The outer ward - magical barriers maintained by apprentices. The party can disable these from inside if they choose.
The senior mages - four of them, each a genuine moral consideration. One has the markings and will freeze before this is over regardless.
Savos Aren himself, with the Eye.
The Dragon Cult They're here too. They've been waiting for this moment. They want to destroy the Eye so Ismara can never complete the ritual. They are not the party's allies. They are an additional pressure.
The Revelation If the party found the vulnerability in Adventure 4, they now have a choice that Ismara doesn't know is available to them. The Eye of Magnus, when brought into resonance with the incomplete matrix of the Ice Crown, would not only power the ritual - it would also stabilize her cognitive matrix so thoroughly that the crown itself would become redundant. She wouldn't need it anymore. It would be safe to remove.
Which means: if they let her complete the ritual, there's a window - brief, violent, dangerous - where the crown could be taken off or destroyed without killing her instantly. What happens to her then is unknown. A Draugr without a mind? A mind without a body? Something else?
Nobody in the story knows this. The party figures it out or they don't.
The Endings
She completes the ritual, keeps the crown. Ismara rules Skyrim. The cold becomes permanent but controlled. Alduin does not return. Winterhold is a monument. The party are her court, whether they like it or not. Complicated. Not purely bad. Not good.
They destroy the crown during the resonance window. Unknown outcome. Possibly her mind survives in the Eye. Possibly she is simply gone. The ritual dissipates. The frozen people unfreeze - most survive. Winterhold can be rebuilt. Alduin's timeline is unaffected - he will return eventually. The party did something genuinely heroic and genuinely terrible.
They let the Dragon Cult destroy the Eye. The ritual fails. Ismara's crown destabilizes. She does not die - she regenerates - but she is diminished, her matrix fractured. The frozen people unfreeze. She retreats. Alduin's return is unimpeded. This is the worst outcome and should feel like it.
They find a third option the GM didn't anticipate. Run with it.

GM NOTES FOR THE PARKS GROUP SPECIFICALLY
On Ismara's presence in towns Don't solve this for them. The first session in Windhelm, she's there. How do they get her inside? Do they try? Do they leave her outside the gates? What does she do while she waits? What do they tell people when asked why a heavily-wrapped figure who doesn't speak is traveling with them? Let them feel the weight of it. Don't intervene. This is the most interesting problem in the whole campaign.
On pacing Each adventure should be 2-3 sessions given how they play. Do not rush the character beats. The Khajiit's relationship with Ismara is the emotional core. Give it room.
On combat Keep fights to one per adventure maximum. Make each one matter. No random encounters. Every hostile NPC has a reason for being there.
On Ismara She is always present but not always active. She observes. She writes brief, direct notes when she needs something. She does not explain herself. If a player asks her a direct question she can answer yes/no with a gesture, she will. Anything more complex she writes. Her Atmoran is archaic but the Khajiit has been around her long enough to start picking up the basics. That should matter.
On the Namira thread Let the Orc player drive it. Don't push. If they lean into it, there's something real there - the locked College chamber, Suvaris in Windhelm, the question of what Namira wants with someone who serves an ice queen. If they don't, it's just texture.
On Hjolmar He's out there. The thread exists in the College archive. If they pull on it hard enough in Adventures 3 or 4, they could find him. He will not be helpful in the way they hope. He's obsessed with his own work and Ismara is his greatest academic achievement. He may not want her destroyed.

That's the framework. Clean, no contrived NPCs, no thralls delivering messages, no omniscient scholars, and no easy answers. Want me to develop any specific adventure in full detail?

