That is genuinely one of the best villain motivations I've heard. Let me say why before I revise anything, because it actually fixes several problems at once.
Why this works perfectly:
The frozen people aren't victims of collateral damage - they are the ritual. Every single one of them, Erik included, Bersi's son, the College apprentice, the villagers - they melt into the ground when it completes. They don't unfreeze. They are consumed and become part of her distributed consciousness. She isn't murdering them. In her framework she is elevating them. They become permanent, immortal, part of something eternal. She genuinely does not understand why mortals would object.
This reframes every moral question in the campaign. The party has been watching her place nodes on living people. They've had to choose whether to participate. Every node placed is someone who will cease to exist as a person. The horror accumulates slowly until the full picture arrives and the players look back at every choice they made.
The Alduin logic becomes airtight. If she IS Skyrim - if her consciousness is the land itself - Alduin cannot end the world without fighting her on her own ground, literally. She becomes unkillable and she becomes Skyrim's immune system simultaneously. It's monstrous and it's brilliant and she knows it.
The revised endgame stakes:
Once the transfer completes, the concept of "killing Ismara" ceases to be meaningful. You cannot kill a continent. The window to stop her is before completion. After that the party's only option would be something nobody in the world knows how to do yet - something that might not even be possible within this campaign's scope.
This means the final adventure's tension isn't "defeat the boss." It's a race. The ritual is active. The Eye is the final power source. If Ismara reaches it and channels it, the transfer initiates and cannot be interrupted. Every decision in the College siege is happening against that clock.
One thing this changes in the framework:
Adventure 4's revelation needs updating. The crown's vulnerability isn't the key anymore - stopping the transfer is. The crown becomes irrelevant the moment the transfer completes. So what the party can discover at Frostmere isn't "here's how to destroy the crown" - it's "here's what she's actually doing and here's how far along it is." The horror of full comprehension. They've been helping her this whole time and now they understand what that means for every frozen person they've walked past.
The endings now become:
She completes the transfer. The frozen people melt. Hundreds of souls become Skyrim itself. Ismara is everywhere and nowhere. The cold lifts. The land feels different - aware. Alduin will never return. The party lives as guests in a country that is watching them. Forever.
They destroy the Eye before she channels it. The ritual fails. The frozen people survive - traumatized, changed, but alive. Ismara still exists as a Draugr with a crown phylactery. She is not stopped, she is set back. Significantly. She will be furious. Alduin's return is unaffected.
They find a way to redirect the transfer. Not to the land. To something smaller. Containable. The Eye itself, perhaps. Ismara as a trapped consciousness inside a stone. Effectively dead but not destroyed. This would require genuine creative problem-solving from the players and should be rewarded if they find it.
They let it complete and then the campaign ends with a hook. Skyrim has a new god. A cold, brilliant, ancient one who was a person once. That's a hell of an epilogue.
