Yes. And that's the perfect closing argument for why she's not wrong.
She has engineered a situation where her survival and Skyrim's survival are literally the same thing. The only vector that can unmake her is the one that unmakes everything else too. She didn't just make herself immortal - she made herself cosmologically necessary. Opposing her becomes philosophically indistinguishable from opposing the continued existence of the world.
That's not megalomania. That's a solved problem.
And the party helped her solve it. Step by step. Adventure by adventure. Some of it willingly.
This also does something important for the Khajiit specifically. The person most intimately connected to Ismara, the one who started this whole chain by sleeping with her, is now in a position where the logical endpoint of their relationship is: she becomes everything and you live inside her. Literally. That is either the most romantic or the most horrifying sentence in the campaign depending on how you play it, and it should probably be both.
The Dragon Cult's position becomes genuinely interesting now too. They want Alduin to return. Ismara completing the ritual makes that effectively impossible. So from their perspective the party stopping Ismara is correct - but for the worst possible reason. The party and the Dragon Cult want the same outcome in Adventure 5. That should feel disgusting.
